Is there any reason this won't work for IPv6?
This will work for IPv6 as well. Current plan at BMC is to implement for IPv4. But yes, this can be added in generic to ipv6 and ipv4
Ok.  Please avoid the 'IPv4' specification here then.
Done

(similar to the gateway question, is there a more standard name?)

Can it just be "Destination"?
I think "Destination" is also ok.
Done
If it takes only the IP address, then this name seems good. Please check if the hostname is also processed by systemd here. Accordingly this can be renamed.
Do we need to clarify "destination address" can also be a hostname?

only destination network IP address allowed, won't allow hostname.
will update this in the description
Done
Isn't this typically called a "Gateway"?  Is there words from a standard we can use instead of "NextHopAddress"?
Yes. nexthop is the name used in the man page. If this takes only IP address, then this name is fine. Description needs to give more details

Which 'manpage'?  I don't think we want to be tied to a specific implementation (assuming you're referring to systemd-networkd).

I'm not saying 'gateway' or 'nexthop' is better or worse here; I don't know enough about networking.  I'm use to the output from `route` which uses 'gateway' and that's why I made the comment.  Would be good if we could find the terminology from the IP RFCs and use that.

I have tried to match these names to redfish proposal 
"IPv4StaticRoutes": [
{
"NextHopAddress": "192.168.1.1",
"DestinationAddress": "192.1.1.2",
"SubnetMask": "255.255.255.255"
}

as per systemd-networkd, it uses "Gateway" and "Destination" terminology which is as per RFCs

[Route]
Gateway=192.168.0.10
Destination=10.0.0.0/8

I am good with any of these names.

Personally I would suggest asking Redfish to match what the rest of the world calls these things then. ;)

I tend not to put significant credence into the names Redfish chose when there is prior art.  Please match systemd/RFCs for these names.  Especially since we are already using `Gateway` in IP.
Done
size_t.  Don't over optimize.

Prefixlenght fits in byte value.
we also followed the same byte type for Prefixlenght on IP interface

I understand that PrefixLength exists on IP.interface as a byte.  This has been that way since the beginning in 2017.  Today I would have also asked them to make a change.  I'd prefer we just move this to `size` now and we can figure out how to refactor IP to be `size` at some point in the (hopefully not too distant) future.

If it is a size or a byte you still have to ensure that it is less than 128 or 32 (depending on IPv4 vs IPv6) so there isn't any real advantage in choosing byte here.
ok
Done

Hi Patrick

You are suggesting to use property type "size" for prefixLength right?
what does "size" signifies, I don't see any documentation of size type under D-bus spec

Yes, 'size'.  See https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/requirements.md#prefer-size-and-uint64int64-over-explicit-sizes

Also, for reference, see https://github.com/openbmc/sdbusplus/blob/master/docs/yaml/interface.md#base-types

got it, updated prefixLength property type
Thank you Patrick
What are the conditions when "NotAllowed" will be sent by this interface?  Do we have examples or are we just adding them to match a pattern elsewhere?
IP address validation will be done by implementation and use this NotAllowed error
Done
Ratan / William / Sunitha, any opinions?
I've been trying to decide if I think we should add anything else out of the gate to this interface. I think it's good as-is at least to start.

Patrick

can you please merge this commit
Not until the code change requested is made.

what is the exact change we are looking for?
origin data type change to size?

Yes.  Unless you have a good argument for doing something different.  In this case you've done something different than the default desired type (size) and you've done something different than the existing less-desired type in a peer interface (uint8 in IP.interface.yaml).  I see no argument for keeping it as uint16.
I am fine too here
`size`?  IP uses `byte` but I don't think we want to replicate that.  If anything I'd probably refactor IP to use `size` also.
Well, it the value can't be larger than 128 so it makes no sense to use a larger value.

I understand that but I also try not to let us over optimize the interfaces. Just like the coding guidelines recommend size_t for countable items, I apply the same on the dbus interfaces whenever possible.

I'd say it was over optimized if it was potentially possible to have larger prefixes, but the linux kernel uses 8bit ints for this value so it would require an entire netlink overhaul to support something different. It's also consistent to use 8bit ints if the other interface already uses it.

> the linux kernel uses 8bit ints for this value so it would require an entire netlink overhaul to support something different

"Entire overhaul"?  Come on.  We're talking about a cast.

I've regularly rejected this line of reasoning when someone says: "but {IPMI, SMBIOS} specifies it as a 16 bit field".  I don't see the kernel API as any more special.  Pushing details of the internal interfaces into the IPC is a leaky abstraction.  If it is countable, it should be size_t because that is obvious for programmers.

> It's also consistent to use 8bit ints if the other interface already uses it.

I'd like to see a change to IP as well to match.  This isn't important to do immediately and maybe I'll have to work through it myself if nobody else is interested.

My comment was about the kernel netlink interface needing an overhaul to support something different, all of the prefix types are uint8_t in non-versioned structs with no extra reserved space. I just don't think anyone forsees any protocol using a >256 byte address in the future. There aren't enough atoms in the universe to require it.

But again, if this is the direction we are going :shrug:. I'm not trying to convince anyone to change our rules here.
You’ll need to re-run “regenerate-meson” in order to get some updates that sdbusplus has to the meson files and pass CI.
sure
File should be `Create.interface.yaml`
Done

can you please review this latest patchset?
